---
import PageLayout from "../../layouts/default-no-header.astro";
const title =
	"Design Studio - Lilla Djurkikaren — Portfolio of Manaj Chakrobarti";
const bodyClass = "works editorial";
import "../../styles/design-studio.scss";
---

<PageLayout title={title} bodyClass={bodyClass}>
	<main class="editorial-page">
		<!-- Full bleed hero — dark left, video right -->
		<div class="hero">
			<div class="inner">
				<!-- Row 1: Title -->
				<h1 class="hero-title">
					Lilla Djurkikaren - a concept to connect young audiences
					with nature so they can discover it in a familiar, playful,
					and accessible way through mixed reality.
				</h1>

				<!-- Row 2: Body + project data -->
				<div class="hero-meta">
					<p class="hero-body">
						Hushållningssällskapet Halland owns a farm, Lilla
						Böslid, near Halmstad. For their mission, they wanted to
						connect a diverse young audience with Swedish nature. We
						worked to create a blended experience so children can
						“uncover the hidden” aspects of farm life through a
						common game of hide-and-seek, while embracing their
						curiosity. We chose this game for its simplicity and for
						its ability to integrate augmented reality through props
						that help them discover animals. We believe this will
						connect them with farm life in a fun way, and they might
						also learn something.
					</p>
					<div class="hero-data">
						<div class="hero-data-item">
							<span class="hero-data-label">Client</span>
							<span class="hero-data-value"
								>Hushållningssällskapet Halland
							</span>
						</div>
						<div class="hero-data-item">
							<span class="hero-data-label"
								>Target audience
							</span>
							<span class="hero-data-value"
								>School kids (6-8 years), Families
							</span>
						</div>

						<div class="hero-data-item">
							<span class="hero-data-label">Design goals </span>
							<span class="hero-data-value">
								Fun and engaging, Collaborative, Educational,
								and Inclusive
							</span>
						</div>

						<div class="hero-data-item">
							<span class="hero-data-label">Design Focus </span>
							<span class="hero-data-value">
								Experience design, Gamification, Augmented
								Reality (AR), and Accessibility
							</span>
						</div>

						<div class="hero-data-item">
							<span class="hero-data-label">Team</span>
							<span class="hero-data-value"
								>Manaj, Dylan, Alireza
							</span>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Row 3: Video -->
				<div class="hero-video">
					<p class="hero-label">
						Here is a 2-minute video to explain the concept.
					</p>
					<video
						controls
						playsinline
						preload="metadata"
						poster="/images/works/design-studio/concept-poster.jpg"
					>
						<source
							src="/images/works/design-studio/concept.mp4"
							type="video/mp4"
						/>
						Your browser does not support the video tag.
					</video>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Sticky sidenav — sits in left [wide] zone -->

		<!-- Article content — sits in [main] zone -->
		<article class="article">
			<nav class="article-navigation">
				<ul class="no-list">
					<li class="no-top-space"><a href="#">Back to top</a></li>
					<li><a href="#background">Background & Challenge </a></li>
					<li><a href="#teams">Team & Responsibilities </a></li>
					<li><a href="#research">Research & Discovery </a></li>
					<li><a href="#concept">Concept Development </a></li>
					<li><a href="#process">Design Process </a></li>
					<li class="no-bottom-space">
						<a href="#reflection">Reflection </a>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</nav>

			<h2 id="background">Background & Challenge</h2>
			<p>
				Hushållningssällskapet Halland is on a mission to welcome
				everyone to the Swedish countryside. On the farm Lilla Böslid,
				they want to share the invisible, tiniest natural marvels among
				people from all walks of life. Because they believe that humans
				find happiness in micro-interactions with nature. However, not
				every visitor can experience these the same way due to their
				limited abilities.
			</p>
			<p>
				For this reason, they want us to design an integrated experience
				primarily for children and others with different abilities,
				using physical touch and digital magnification to make the
				hidden details of the wetlands and farm exciting and accessible,
				but not overwhelming
			</p>
			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/lillaboslid-gmap.png"
					alt="Google map image of Lilla Böslid Area"
				/>
				<figcaption>Lilla Böslid Area from Google Maps</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<h2 id="teams">Team & Responsibilities</h2>
			<p>
				This was a group project of three people, Alireza, Dylan, and
				me, Manaj. We participated equally throughout ideation and
				brainstorming sessions. Nonetheless, we leveraged our individual
				strengths. For example, I worked with programming and graphic
				design software; Alierza helped me with programming, and he also
				worked in video direction; and Dylan worked on physical
				prototypes.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/team.png"
					alt="Team picture"
				/>
				<figcaption>
					From left to right, Manaj, Alireza, and Dylan
				</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>
				Every brainstorming session led to our decision through
				arguments. Since the beginning, we wanted to provide a solution
				that is immersive and educational. But through debating ideas,
				we could land on a fun and engaging solution.
			</p>
			<p>
				Håkan was our contact person from the farm. We updated him with
				our preliminary plans, and with his opinion, we shaped our
				solution. We showed him three options, and we merged two based
				on his preference.
			</p>

			<h2 id="research">Research & Discovery</h2>
			<p>
				Our research started with a site visit. Lilla Böslid has several
				buildings, a restaurant, ponds, grassy fields, and jungle areas.
				It's a beautiful green space, and we took a lot of pictures.
				From this visit, we found:
			</p>
			<div class="image-pair">
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/open-space.png"
						alt="Open fields "
					/>
					<figcaption>Open fields</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/pond.png"
						alt="There are several ponds"
					/>
					<figcaption>There are several ponds</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>
			<ol>
				<li>
					The farm has sufficient space to host a big group of
					children for activities
				</li>
				<li>It lacks animal</li>
				<li>Finally, the landscape has variety in this space</li>
			</ol>

			<p>
				After that, our next logical step was to find similar facilities
				and potential competitors. We found “Naturum Getterön”, a
				similar facility far from Halmstad, that offers extensive
				bird-related activities, such as watching and playing in
				structures shaped like birds. From their <a
					href="https://www.naturumgetteron.se/naturum/"
					target="_blank"
				>
					website</a
				>, “We offer guided tours, lectures, a shop and a café with a
				fantastic view of the area. Downstairs we also have a
				family-friendly exhibition about bird life …”. From this desk
				research, we came to the conclusion that:
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					They are more focused on education than on fun activities.
				</li>
				<li>They don't have any games and a few activities.</li>
			</ol>
			<p>
				We wanted to learn more about mixed reality projects, so we
				visited the IKEA Museum to check it out. We were surprised to
				see that while there are so many things, like you can push a
				boulder in the screen using a lever, a group of children were
				playing some sort of tag and running and screaming. We
				understood that:
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					Playing is more important for this group than experiencing
					something new. Although this was a very small sample.
				</li>
				<li>
					They prefer playing together when there is more than one
					person.
				</li>
			</ol>
			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/ikea.jpg"
					alt=" Ikea Musuem, Älmhult"
				/>
				<figcaption>Ikea Musuem, Älmhult</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<p>
				We failed to secure interviews with both children and teachers,
				acting as “proxies for users” from the different schools in the
				area. So we interview some children around the community
				informally. Before that, we also looked into popular games and
				AR-based experiences on mobile phones. We found an AR
				application that can place an animal in the room with a tap on
				the screen. We showed this to the children, and they were
				excited to see it. From this session, we found:
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>Young children feel excited seeing animals</li>
				<li>
					They like being in social or group activities, because one
					of the children was showing her sister's profile in the
					Roblox app that we tested.
				</li>
				<li>
					Finally, we also found that parents don't really like the
					idea of their children using mobile phones. Almost all of
					them have restrictions on phone use.
				</li>
			</ol>
			<figure class="wide">
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/research.png"
					alt="Research Synthesis "
				/>
				<figcaption>Research Synthesis</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>
				From the research findings, it became increasingly clear to us
				that we want a solution that's fun first, but we can’t give
				mobile phones to the audience at any point because that
				conflicts with the idea of visiting nature.
			</p>

			<h2 id="concept">Concept Development</h2>
			<p>
				From the inception of this project, we were brainstorming ideas
				about using pseudoreality, like spyglass, to see seasonal
				changes, augmentation, like placing animals in the void using
				mobile phones, using sound to listen for the hidden life of the
				pond, and educational concepts like teaching farming. Based on
				our research, we decided to create a fun group activity. And
				that has to include the one person who is behind the spyglass.
				There is a simple, outdoor, fun, no-instructions-needed, and
				familiar game like that: hide-and-seek.
			</p>
			<p>
				We transformed a common game of hide-and-seek into a game of
				hiding toy animals near a platform. The platform will have a
				spyglass to locate the animal, and there will be speakers on the
				platform that play sound clues to guide the animal's location.
				Once the observer finds it, they can show it to other people.
				And that way, each of them can take turns hiding and seeking it.
			</p>

			<h2 id="process">Design Process</h2>
			<h3>Ideation</h3>
			<p>
				Our ideation process involved long brainstorming sessions. These
				sessions helped us think through the brief, research insights,
				and generate ideas. We documented these sessions through writing
				in the notebooks and maintaining Figma boards for each week.
				Later, we also utilized storyboarding to detail each idea. This
				helped us understand the user journey throughout the gameplay.
			</p>

			<div class="image-pair">
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/mindmap.png"
						alt="Sample of mind map"
					/>
					<figcaption>
						Mindmap, Image credit: Alireza, from his notes
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/storyboard.png"
						alt="Storyboard Image"
					/>
					<figcaption>Storyboard, a snap from my notebook</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<h3>Prototyping & testing</h3>
			<p>
				We used prototypes at varying levels of fidelity to visualize
				our ideas. Starting from sketching on paper to a lo-fi prototype
				using cardboard. Each fidelity led us to the hi-fidelity
				prototype we delivered, whether it was a digital mobile
				application or a physical spyglass.
			</p>
			<div class="image-pair">
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/sketch.png"
						alt="SketPrototype sketching "
					/>
					<figcaption>
						Prototype sketching, Image credit: Dylan
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<img
						src="/images/works/design-studio/prototype.png"
						alt="Cardboard Prototypes "
					/>
					<figcaption>Cardboard Prototypes</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>
			<p>
				We tested our lo-fi physical prototype with our peers at the
				beginning to see if it could deliver the feeling of seeing
				augmented animals through the spyglass. We found that the
				spyglass was hard to hold, so we changed its shape to a cone.
				Additionally, we realized it's too heavy to hold in the hand,
				even for us, so we introduced a tripod to support the spyglass.
			</p>

			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/timetwist.jpg"
					alt="Picture of Testing physical prototype"
				/>
				<figcaption>Testing physical prototype</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<p>
				Later, once we had our concept finalized and high-fidelity
				props, we tested with a real user (an 8-year-old girl) to see
				whether the whole concept works with the spyglass and mobile
				application, and to guide her in a specific direction with an
				animal sound. From this test, we found that the mobile app's
				viewing area was way too wide, so we changed it to a zoomed-in
				view of the scene to convey the feeling of looking through a
				spyglass.
			</p>

			<figure class="wide">
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/user-test.jpg"
					alt="User testing session"
				/>
				<figcaption>User testing session</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<h3>Iterations</h3>
			<p>
				We iterated on ideas, Spyglass, and mobile applications over
				several rounds to arrive at our final concept. Our first concept
				had a picture taken at the end of the animal's finding. We left
				it because it didn’t include the person who is on the spyglass.
				Also, this might be interesting for parents, but we noticed
				during our testing session that kids do not look happy while
				taking pictures
			</p>
			<p>
				The hide-and-seek idea came to us later in the project during a
				brainstorming session with our mentor Bertil, and we were in the
				process of using sound as our beacon to find the animal. And
				Bertil came up with the idea of using a hide-and-seek prop
				during gameplay. Which we all welcomed and added to the
				storyboard.
			</p>
			<p>
				Another change we had to make in the physical prototype: the
				first version showed much more than the device's screen, so it
				did not convey the feeling of looking through the spyglass.
				Also, the rest of the screen was visible, which didn't feel like
				a spyglass, so Dylan made a version that blocks the view of the
				rest of the screen on the mobile device. This one we used to
				shoot our concept video; at the end, it broke, and the cover
				that blocked the mobile's view felt too soft. So, in the last
				version, he made it sturdier.
			</p>

			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/iterations.png"
					alt="Picture of physical prototype iterations"
				/>
				<figcaption>Physical prototype iterations</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>
				Similarly, the application we used underwent some iterations
				based on changes to the concept and to the application within
				the same concept. For example, the first concept was a photo
				feature that required a button, but we later removed it. At the
				end of the app, we have a bare-bones version without any UI
				components, due to inaccessibility within Spyglass.
			</p>

			<figure>
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/app-iterations.png"
					alt="Picture of iPhone application iterations"
				/>
				<figcaption>iPhone application iterations</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<h3>Experience Overview</h3>
			<p>
				We created three parts of the experience: first, the spyglass;
				second, the app; and, finally, the platform with a sound system
				and toy animals to hide. They joined to provide a cohesive
				experience for the children.
			</p>

			<figure class="wide">
				<img
					src="/images/works/design-studio/solution.png"
					alt="Picture of Three parts of the experience
"
				/>
				<figcaption>Three parts of the experience</figcaption>
			</figure>

			<h2 id="reflection">Reflection</h2>
			<p>
				We received praise from the client as a designer, and we
				delivered on time. I learned a ton about editing software like
				Davinci Resolve while editing and adding sound in the concept
				video. Another big achievement was to vibe-code for the first
				time and build an iPhone application using Claude AI. And it
				changed the philosophy I believed in. I used to think that
				taking help from AI would lose my originality. Now I learned not
				to look at it egoistically, but rather to look at the quality of
				the final deliverables and the problem it solves. Which I feel
				is great progress as a designer.
			</p>

			<p>
				We also didn't want to use mobile phones, as we found that
				parents don't like their kids using them. However, we ended up
				using one because creating an AI-enabled square screen is
				extremely expensive, and we don't have the technical ability to
				do so. This also forced us to compromise on the spyglass design;
				we could make it look more like a real spyglass.
			</p>
			<p>
				We assumed we would be able to find children to test our design,
				but we couldn’t. So we tested with only one child from our
				personal network. Which made me insecure about the concept.
			</p>
			<p>
				Additionally, we only proposed a wheelchair-friendly pathway to
				the platform, and the tripod supports vertical position changes.
				Similarly, proposed headphones for the hearing-impaired kids.
				But we haven’t done much for visually impaired kids.
			</p>
			<p>
				Finally, philosophically, I like using AR animals to teach kids,
				which is speculating but I feel that if everyone uses technology
				to teach about animals, we won't need zoos that trap them.
			</p>
			<hr class="divider">
		</article>
	</main>

	<script>
		const nav = document.querySelector(".article-navigation");
		const hero = document.querySelector(".hero");

		if (nav && hero) {
			const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
				([entry]) => {
					if (!entry.isIntersecting) {
						nav.classList.add("is-visible");
					} else {
						nav.classList.remove("is-visible");
					}
				},
				{ threshold: 0 },
			);

			observer.observe(hero);
		}
	</script>
	<script>
		const figures = document.querySelectorAll(".article figure");

		const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
			(entries) => {
				entries.forEach((entry) => {
					if (entry.isIntersecting) {
						entry.target.classList.add("is-visible");
						observer.unobserve(entry.target);
					}
				});
			},
			{ threshold: 0.1 },
		);

		figures.forEach((el) => observer.observe(el));
	</script>
</PageLayout>
